The expanded regional tier (networkCount 35\'9641) has the worst documentation rate at **75.7%** blank \'97 3 in 4 searches with no reason entered. Even the best-documented tier, statewide searches (429\'96576 cameras), has a 43.6% blank rate. The key point for the Board: there is no network scope at which documentation practices come close to adequate. Searches querying hundreds of agencies\'92 cameras across California are being conducted, undocumented, at the same rate as purely local queries.\
\
Because Yuba County\'92s improper documentation is visible on the public Transparency Portal without requiring a CPRA request, it is already on the public record and creates direct legal accountability exposure for the agency. A Flock camera was also identified in **Sutter County** via the deflock.me map. That contract does not appear easily findable through public web searches \'97 a CPRA request to Sutter County may be needed to confirm deployment details.\
\
# **4. YCSO Public Communications \'97 Flock Notification Framing**\
\
The Yuba County Sheriff\'92s Office publishes monthly \'93numbers\'94 graphics on its official Facebook page, juxtaposing Flock notifications alongside arrests, bookings, and property crime counts. Analysis of 25 months of available posts (July 2023 through November 2025) reveals a pattern of presentation that is materially misleading to the public regarding Flock\'92s effectiveness.\
\
## **The Definition Problem: What a**** ****\'93****Flock Notification****\'94**** ****Actually Is**\
\
Beginning in approximately mid-2024, the YCSO added a fine-print disclaimer defining the Flock figure: *\'93**A Flock notification refers to an alert into Dispatch that a car passing one of the Flock cameras throughout the County is stolen or associated with an AMBER Alert or serious crime.**\'94*\
\
By the YCSO\'92s own definition, a Flock notification is an automated camera alert to dispatch \'97 not an investigation, not a search, not a stop, and not an arrest. The number represents flagged-plate detections, which may include duplicate detections of the same vehicle, detections never acted upon, and alerts dispatch received but deputies did not respond to.\
\
## **The Framing Problem: Visual Association Without Causal Link**\
\
Despite the disclaimer\'92s technical accuracy, the graphic design of each monthly post places Flock notifications in direct visual proximity to the arrests figure \'97 presented in the same box, at the same type size, under the same heading. There is no explanatory text connecting or separating these metrics. The reasonable public inference is that Flock notifications contributed to arrests. That inference is not supported by any data the YCSO has published.\
\
The earlier posts (July 2023, August 2023, December 2023, January 2024) used the term \'93Flock Hits\'94 with no definition at all \'97 an even less accountable presentation. The subsequent addition of the disclaimer represents a tacit acknowledgment that the prior framing was unclear, yet the visual juxtaposition with arrests was preserved throughout.\
\
