## **Questions for the Board of Supervisors**\
\
- Of the Flock notifications reported each month, how many resulted in a deputy being dispatched to investigate?\
\
- Of those dispatched responses, how many resulted in a stop or contact with a vehicle or person?\
\
- Of those contacts, how many resulted in an arrest, citation, or recovery of stolen property?\
\
- Has the YCSO ever produced an internal analysis of Flock\'92s notification-to-arrest conversion rate? If so, why has it not been shared with the Board or the public?\
\
- Is the Measure K Citizens Oversight Committee aware that the effectiveness metric routinely cited \'97 Flock notifications \'97 is an automated alert count with no established connection to enforcement outcomes?\
\
# **5. The Transparency Portal Is Not SB 34 Compliance**\
\
The Flock Safety Transparency Portal is a public-facing product feature controlled by Flock Safety, the vendor. Flock determines which fields are visible, which are redacted, and what is omitted entirely. It is not a legal compliance document \'97 it is a marketing and public relations tool that happens to contain some audit data. The YCSO\'92s SB 34 compliance obligations are entirely independent of what Flock chooses to publish.\
\
## **What SB 34 Actually Requires**\
\
California Vehicle Code \'a7 2413 (SB 34) requires the **agency** \'97 not the vendor \'97 to maintain an ALPR usage policy and audit logs sufficient to demonstrate that every search was conducted for an authorized purpose, by an authorized user, in connection with an active investigation. YCSO\'92s SB 34-compliant internal logs should contain everything visible on the portal plus:\
\
- The unredacted user identity and badge or employee ID behind each search.\
\
- The specific case number the search was tied to.\
\
- Any supervisory authorization or notes beyond the reason field.\
\
- A complete, unedited edit history showing whether reason fields were modified after the fact.\
\
## **The Compliance Gap**\
\
If YCSO is relying solely on the Transparency Portal as its SB 34 audit log \'97 with user IDs redacted and no case-level linkage \'97 it is not in compliance with the statute. A Phase 2 CPRA request for the internal unredacted logs will resolve this one of two ways:\
\
- **The logs exist and are more complete than the portal** \'97 in which case YCSO has been presenting a sanitized public view while withholding the full compliance record.\
\
- **The logs do not exist beyond what is on the portal** \'97 in which case YCSO has been out of SB 34 compliance for the entire duration of Flock\'92s deployment.\
\
# **6. Two Data Streams, One Accountability Gap**\
\
Two independent data sources are now available for this research: the YCSO\'92s monthly Facebook statistics (25 months, July 2023\'96November 2025) and the daily scrape of the Flock Safety Transparency Portal search audit logs. These data streams measure fundamentally different things \'97 and the gap between them is itself an accountability finding.\
\
## **What Each Dataset Measures**\
\
**Facebook**** ****\'93****Flock Notifications****\'94****:**** **Automated camera alerts fired to dispatch when a flagged plate passes a Flock camera. One vehicle passing multiple cameras generates multiple notifications. There is no published data on how many notifications were acted upon.\
\
**Transparency Portal Search Audit Logs:**** **Active queries initiated by a deputy or dispatcher against the Flock database. This is a human-initiated action that SB 34 requires to be documented with a reason. Approximately 53% of these entries have no reason recorded.\
\
## **The Gap Between the Two**\
\
The full chain of events \'97 from camera detection through dispatch alert through search through enforcement action through case outcome \'97 is completely invisible in any public data. This invisibility is not a technical limitation \'97 it is a governance failure.\
\
- **The Transparency Portal** shows searches with no documented justification (53% blank reason rate) \'97 a compliance failure at the point of human action.\
\
- **The Facebook data** shows notifications with no documented outcomes \'97 a transparency failure at the point of automated detection.\
\
- Neither dataset connects to the other.\
\
# **7. Effectiveness Claims and Confounding Variables**\
\
Law enforcement agencies, including Yuba County, cite improved crime clearance rates as a primary justification for Flock investment. These claims deserve scrutiny because clearance rate data cannot isolate Flock\'92s contribution from other simultaneous changes.\
\
## **The Attribution Problem**\
\
A crime is \'93cleared\'94 when an arrest is made or the case is exceptionally cleared. Home surveillance cameras (Ring, Nest, Blink) have expanded dramatically over the same 2021\'962026 period during which Flock was deployed in Yuba County. When an agency claims Flock improved clearance rates, there is a significant **attribution problem**: the same outcome could have been driven entirely by resident-provided footage, neighborhood tip networks, or other factors unrelated to ALPR searches.\
\
## **Specific Confounders for Property Crimes**\
\
- Doorbell and driveway cameras are now standard in many Yuba County residential areas. Homeowners frequently share footage directly with investigators, often resolving cases with no ALPR involvement.\
\
- Neighborhood platforms such as Nextdoor and Ring\'92s Neighbors app facilitate rapid informal tip-sharing that can lead to arrests entirely outside the Flock system.\
\
- Deterrence effects of visible home cameras may independently reduce property crime, shrinking the denominator of crimes committed while Flock receives credit for any cases that are cleared.\
\
- **Staffing changes** funded by Measure K (26 new sheriff\'92s department positions) represent an independent variable that could improve clearance rates regardless of any surveillance technology.\
\
## **Questions for the Board of Supervisors**\
\
- Were clearance rates broken down by crime type and compared against a pre-Flock baseline that accounts for concurrent changes in home surveillance density?\
\
- Is there case-level documentation linking specific Flock ALPR hits to cleared cases, as opposed to cases cleared through resident footage, tips, or other means?\
\
- How have clearance rates for crimes not typically involving vehicles \'97 where ALPR would have no relevance \'97 changed over the same period?\
\
- What methodology was used to attribute clearance rate improvements specifically to Flock, and has that methodology been independently reviewed?\
\
The core argument is not that Flock never contributes to clearances \'97 it is that the county has accepted significant civil liberties risks and ongoing taxpayer expense based on effectiveness claims that are **methodologically unsupportable** without controls for these confounding variables.\
\
# **8. Measure K \'97 The Funding Mechanism**\
\
Measure K is a local sales tax approved by Yuba County voters to fund public safety. It has funded Flock cameras, body-worn cameras, upgraded dispatch systems, and 26 new sheriff\'92s department positions. Voters approved Measure K for broad \'93public safety\'94 purposes \'97 they were not specifically informed that funds would go toward a Flock surveillance system with documented security vulnerabilities and SB 34 compliance gaps.\
\
# **9. Conflict of Interest \'97 Undersheriff Morawczewski**\
\
Undersheriff Morawczewski chairs the Measure K Citizens Oversight Committee \'97 the body responsible for independently evaluating how Measure K funds are spent. He also manages the sheriff\'92s department that directly benefits from those funds. This is a textbook conflict of interest under **California Government Code Section 1090**, which prohibits public officials from participating in decisions where they have a direct material interest. A complaint could be filed with the Fair Political Practices Commission (FPPC) or the county counsel.\
\
## **The Oversight Committee \'97 Four Years of Theatre**\
\
From August 2022 through February 2026, the Measure K Citizens Oversight Committee has met with nearly identical bare-bones agendas: elect officers, approve minutes, receive department updates, set future dates, and adjourn. There has been no substantive examination of specific expenditures, no scrutiny of Flock\'92s compliance with SB 34, and no independent review of how the surveillance system is being used.\
\
# **10. Supervisor Bradford \'97 Community Engagement**\
\
On the Plumas Lake subreddit, Supervisor Bradford defended Flock by citing the sheriff\'92s characterization of it as a \'93game changer\'94 and pointing to the Flock transparency portal. When pressed for specific statistics, he admitted he had none and said he would ask the sheriff for data.\
\
# **11. Quarterly Public Safety Presentation**\
\
A June 2024 Yuba County Board of Supervisors meeting video shows Undersheriff Morawczewski presenting quarterly public safety statistics and referencing Flock\'92s impact. Critically, this presentation does not appear in the official meeting minutes \'97 a transparency gap in itself.\
\
# **12. Documented Flock Security Vulnerabilities**\
\
- Senator Ron Wyden\'92s investigation found Flock does not require multi-factor authentication.\
\
- At least 35 customer account passwords were stolen by hackers.\
\
- Flock cameras and admin dashboards were publicly accessible at one point.\
\
- A Texas case documented deputies using Flock to track a woman across 83,000 cameras.\
\
- In Joplin, Missouri, an officer abused the system for over a year before it was caught.\
\
- February 2026: A Milwaukee officer was charged with misconduct after performing 179 Flock searches to track the person he was dating and their ex-partner.\
\
- 2024: A Kansas police chief was charged with using cameras to track his ex-girlfriend.\
\
- November 2025: A Georgia police chief was charged with using cameras to stalk and harass private citizens.\
\
# **13. Presentation Strategy ****&**** Communication Approach**\
\
## **The**** ****\'93****Fresh Eyes****\'94**** ****Advantage**\
\
This research was conducted by someone new to local government, public records practice, and Board of Supervisors proceedings. That is a strategic asset, not a liability.\
\
*Suggested opening framing:** **\'93**I\'92m new to this process, so I came in without assumptions about how things work. Here\'92s what the data showed when I looked at it fresh.**\'94*\
\
## **Policy Criticism, Not Personal Attack**\
\
- Lead with \'93the system lacks adequate oversight\'94 rather than \'93the sheriff is misusing this tool.\'94\
\
- Frame the Measure K oversight committee as a structural failure, not a personal one.\
\
- Present the conflict of interest issue as a policy problem requiring a structural fix, not a character indictment.\
\
- Acknowledge that law enforcement faces real challenges \'97 the argument is about accountability mechanisms, not intent.\
\
## **Handling the**** ****\'93****Your Phone Already Tracks You****\'94**** ****Argument**\
\
- **Consent and control:**** **You chose your phone and can theoretically opt out. You cannot opt out of driving on public roads past a Flock camera.\
\
- **Power asymmetry:**** **Private companies have some liability for misuse; government databases can be accessed across agencies with weaker controls.\
\
- **Legal trajectory:**** ***Carpenter v. United States* (2018) established that aggregate location patterns deserve Fourth Amendment protection. Courts are applying that logic increasingly broadly.\
\
## **National Surveillance Context: The FBI Admission (March 2026)**\
\
On March 18, 2026, FBI Director Kash Patel testified before the Senate Intelligence Committee and confirmed that the FBI is actively purchasing commercially available location data on Americans \'97 without warrants. Senator Ron Wyden called it \'93an outrageous end run around the Fourth Amendment.\'94\
\
Three distinctions to keep sharp when a Board member suggests ubiquitous surveillance makes Flock concerns moot:\
\
- **Your phone** \'97 voluntary, private-sector, and subject to Carpenter constraints if government seeks access.\
\
- **Federal data brokers** \'97 no consent, no warrant, no local accountability.\
\
- **Yuba County\'92s Flock system** \'97 government-operated, locally funded by Measure K, and governed by SB 34. There is a specific legal framework that applies here.\
\
**Important caveat:**** **The law has not yet clearly prohibited Flock-style surveillance. The honest framing is not \'93this is illegal\'94 but \'93this is a governance gap the law has not yet closed, and here\'92s why it should.\'94 Overstating the legal case undermines credibility.\
\
