# **15. Statewide Flock Accountability \'97 Tiburon Case Study**\
\
*Source: The Ark (Tiburon, CA),** **\'93**Ark investigation: Follow-up audit finds far broader access to Tiburon license-plate data,**\'94** **March 25, 2026. Executive Editor Kevin Hessel.*\
\
**Scope note for YCSO data:**** **The YCSO dataset collected for this project begins February 2, 2026 \'97 approximately six weeks after Flock\'92s December 16, 2025 system changes described below. This means the YCSO\'92s ~53% blank-reason rate is already a post-change baseline. The pre-December era of candidly entered free-text reasons (e.g., \'93DEA assist,\'94 \'93IC\uc0\u1045 ,\'94 \'93abortion\'94) is not captured in the data. The changes documented here provide important context for interpreting what the YCSO data does \'97 and does not \'97 show.\
\
## **The Scale of the Problem**\
\
The Ark\'92s independent audit of Tiburon\'92s Flock system found 41 California law-enforcement agencies conducted 16,029 potentially illegal searches of Tiburon\'92s license plate logs in just six months \'97 18 more agencies than the Tiburon Police Department identified in its own audit of the same period. The department\'92s self-audit keyword approach would have missed nearly 97% of searches.\
\
Among the searches: Santa Clara police cited \'93DEA assist\'94 100 times; the Riverside County District Attorney\'92s Office wrote \'93ATF aid\'94; Elk Grove cited the Oregon State Police; West Covina, Murrieta, and Glendora police all indicated they searched for federal warrants.\
\
## **The Drop-Down Change: Concealment by Design (~December 16, 2025)**\
\
Around December 16, 2025, Flock rolled out a system change to all California agencies: the free-text-only reason field was replaced with a standardized drop-down menu of crime categories (e.g., \'93Burglary/Breaking & Entering,\'94 \'93Larceny/Theft Offenses,\'94 \'93Traffic Infraction\'94) drawn from a federal crime-reporting framework. A free-text suffix field still exists but is now optional.\
\
The effect, according to the ACLU of Northern California and EFF:\
\
- With preselected categories accepted as sufficient to trigger a search, many agencies have stopped filling in the free-text field \'97 eliminating auditable phrases like \'93DEA assist\'94 or \'93immigration.\'94\
\
- A filter blocks certain keywords \'97 including immigration and reproductive health care terms \'97 from being entered as reasons. But the filter applies only to labeling, not to what data officers can access. An officer who receives an error can immediately retry the same search under a different category.\
\
- A search conducted to assist a federal immigration task force is now recorded identically to a routine stolen-vehicle lookup \'97 unless the officer voluntarily adds detail.\
\
- The result is cleaner logs that police and Flock can point to as proof of compliance, even if actual search behavior has not changed.\
\
*\'93**These drop-downs effectively give law enforcement options for how to avoid being transparent and honest about why they\'92re using the system.**\'94* \'97 Nick Hidalgo, ACLU of Northern California\
\
**Implication for YCSO data:**** **The YCSO\'92s ~53% blank-reason rate, drawn from post-December 16 data, likely understates the pre-change documentation problem. The drop-down standardization may also explain why reason entries in the YCSO data are inconsistently formatted \'97 some deputies may be supplementing the drop-down with free text while others are not.\
\
## **Flock Strips Officer Names and Plate Data from Audit Logs**\
\
In a separate change, Flock has stripped officer names and the specific plate numbers queried from what the company calls Network Audit Logs \'97 the records host agencies use to see how outside agencies have searched their data. Where an officer\'92s name once appeared, agencies now see only an alphanumeric identifier. The license plate that was searched is gone entirely.\
\
The EFF\'92s Dave Maass was direct: *\'93**If Flock is not releasing the username of the person anymore to the agency, that agency is noncompliant with SB 34. Just right off the bat. Removing from the network audits the name of the officer who ran the case and the plate \'97 that\'92s just against the law. Period.**\'94*\
\
California law (Civil Code \'a7 1798.90.52) requires agencies to maintain a record of every search including, at minimum: the date and time, the license plate or other data queried, the username of the person who accessed the information, and their organizational affiliation. **Flock\'92s change puts every California client agency in automatic non-compliance with this requirement.**\
\
**Implication for YCSO:**** **If YCSO\'92s internal logs rely on Flock-supplied Network Audit Log data for external agency tracking, those logs are now structurally incomplete under SB 34. This is a direct follow-up question for the Phase 2 CPRA request: does YCSO\'92s internal audit log contain full officer names and plate data for all searches, or has it been degraded by Flock\'92s changes?\
\
## **The Self-Audit Problem: Structural Impossibility**\
\
The Tiburon investigation illustrates why self-auditing is structurally inadequate for Flock deployments. No local agency can identify every task force, subunit, and embedded federal relationship across hundreds of partner agencies statewide. Tiburon\'92s keyword-based audit found roughly 3 in 100 federally-entangled searches.\
\
The Ark\'92s audit identified violations from agencies citing HIDTA (High Intensity Drug Trafficking Areas, a federally administered DEA program), Homeland Security, the FBI\'92s Joint Terrorism Task Force, and out-of-state law enforcement \'97 categories Tiburon\'92s audit terms did not include. The same structural blind spots apply to YCSO.\
\
## **Flock\'92s Growing Accountability Problem Nationally**\
\
- 53 cities in 20 states have rejected or canceled Flock contracts in the past year.\
\
- Denver ended its contract in February 2026, specifically citing federal immigration agents\'92 use of the platform.\
\
- South Pasadena and Ithaca, New York, terminated contracts citing privacy concerns.\
\
- Lynnwood, Washington, canceled after finding more than 100,000 unauthorized searches.\
\
- A class-action lawsuit filed February 26, 2026 in San Francisco Superior Court names Flock as an ALPR \'93operator\'94 with independent legal obligations under state privacy law. Among the plaintiffs is a San Rafael resident who passes 12 Flock cameras on his daily commute.\
\
- San Jose voted to keep its 474-camera network but cut data retention from one year to 30 days, banned cameras near abortion clinics and places of worship, and required officers to document a case number for each search.\
\
## **The Warrant Argument**\
\
The ACLU\'92s Hidalgo argues that under the California Constitution, retrospective database searches \'97 the kind that account for virtually every search in the Tiburon and YCSO data \'97 should require a warrant. The distinction is between **hot-list searches** (automated alert when a specific flagged plate is seen \'97 targeted, immediate, narrow) and **retrospective database searches** (an officer queries the entire logged history for a plate, assembling a comprehensive record of movements across days or weeks).\
\
*\'93**What Flock cameras can do is paint a shockingly and disturbingly accurate picture of our lives.**\'94* \'97 Nick Hidalgo, ACLU of Northern California\
\
A hearing in the San Jose retrospective-search warrant case is scheduled for early August 2026 \'97 potentially producing a ruling before or shortly after the planned June Board of Supervisors presentation. This is worth monitoring.\
\
## **Questions for the Board of Supervisors**\
\
- Has YCSO reviewed its Flock search logs for searches citing federal agencies, out-of-state agencies, or joint task forces with embedded federal agents? What did that review find?\
\
- Now that Flock has removed officer names and plate numbers from Network Audit Logs, how does YCSO maintain compliance with California Civil Code \'a7 1798.90.52, which requires logs to include the username and organizational affiliation for every search?\
\
- Were YCSO deputies instructed on how to use the new drop-down reason categories after Flock\'92s December 2025 system change? Is there a policy requiring the optional free-text field to be completed?\
\
- Is YCSO aware that the California AG\'92s 2024 ALPR policy template calls for specific details \'97 including a case number \'97 to tether each search to a documented investigation? Does YCSO\'92s policy comply with that template?\
