# **16. OMNIA Contract Analysis \'97 Retention Conflict and Permitting SOP**\
\
*Source: OMNIA Partners cooperative contract RS250203 \'97 Flock Group Inc.\'a0dba Flock Safety / Region 4 Education Service Center, effective April 1, 2025. Produced via CPRA, April 2026.*\
\
The OMNIA cooperative purchasing contract through which YCSO procured Flock services contains Flock\'92s own representations to a national procurement body about how its product works and how installations are conducted. These representations carry independent evidentiary weight because they reflect Flock\'92s baseline standard of practice \'97 not terms negotiated locally with YCSO.\
\
## **Finding 1: Three-Way Data Retention Conflict**\
\
The OMNIA contract\'92s product description states explicitly: *\'93**LPR images are stored for 30 days by default unless a differing local law/ordinance/agreement/etc. dictates otherwise**\'94* (OMNIA contract, lines 1977\'961979). This 30-day default is also reflected throughout the product pricing table, where every standard Falcon camera subscription is described as including \'9330 days storage.\'94\
\
This creates a three-way conflict in YCSO\'92s retention framework:\
\
**Source** | **Retention Term** |\
\
\'97 | \'97 |\
\
Flock OMNIA contract / product standard | 30 days (default) |\
\
YCSO Policy 433 | 60 days |\
\
Flock Master Services Agreement (YCSO) | Up to one year |\
\
YCSO\'92s 60-day Policy 433 retention period is not Flock\'92s default \'97 it is a non-standard configuration that required deliberate deviation from Flock\'92s baseline. That deviation is not documented in any publicly available record. No Board resolution, no contract addendum, and no documented public process establishes why YCSO chose 60 days rather than the vendor\'92s standard 30 days. The MSA\'92s \'93up to one year\'94 provision creates further upward pressure: YCSO could, under contract, retain data for a full year \'97 twelve times longer than Flock\'92s stated default \'97 without any additional public authorization.\
\
**The governance question for the Board:** Who authorized YCSO\'92s 60-day retention period, under what authority, and why is that deviation not reflected in any publicly available documentation?\
\
## **Finding 2: Flock\'92s Own Permitting Commitment**\
\
In its OMNIA proposal, Flock described its standard implementation process as follows: *\'93**all locations will go through Permitting with Flock prior to installation. Field Technicians will come onsite to install all cameras**\'94* (OMNIA contract, lines 529\'96532).\
\
This is Flock\'92s own declared standard operating procedure, submitted to a national procurement body under certification. Pre-installation permitting is not presented as optional or agency-dependent \'97 it is described as a routine step Flock coordinates before any camera goes up.\
\
This directly strengthens the Public Works Track B argument. YCSO\'92s Public Works MOU covers only the Starbend Boat Ramp camera. If Plumas Lake installations lack encroachment permits or equivalent documented authorization, those installations did not follow Flock\'92s own contractually-declared SOP. The absence of Public Works records is not just a local governance gap \'97 it is a departure from what Flock itself commits to as standard practice.\
\
**Note:** Track B CPRA response to Public Works is pending (filed April 10, 2026; response target ~April 20). Absence of permit records, if confirmed, should be presented alongside Flock\'92s OMNIA language as independent corroboration that permits were required and should exist.\
\
## **Finding 3: No Proprietary Information \'97 All Contract Terms Are Public**\
\
Flock selected Option A in the OMNIA open records certification: *\'93**No proprietary information**\'94* (OMNIA contract, line 1215). This means Flock made no claim of trade-secret protection over any portion of its proposal or contract terms.\
\
The practical effect for YCSO: if YCSO attempts to withhold contract terms, pricing, or implementation specifications in response to a CPRA request by claiming Flock\'92s materials are proprietary, that claim is refuted by Flock\'92s own certification. The door is closed.\
\
## **Finding 4: Agency Data Ownership Forecloses Vendor Deflection**\
\
The OMNIA contract confirms that agencies own 100% of the data Flock collects on their behalf (line 1970). This directly affects how YCSO can respond to questions about audit log integrity and the December 2025 portal changes.\
\
When Flock removed officer names and plate numbers from Network Audit Logs, some agencies have suggested this is Flock\'92s responsibility rather than theirs. The data ownership clause undercuts that deflection. If the agency owns the data, the agency is responsible for ensuring its audit logs are complete and compliant with SB 34 \'97 regardless of what Flock\'92s platform chooses to display or withhold in its portal interface. YCSO cannot outsource its SB 34 compliance obligations to Flock\'92s product decisions.\
\
## **Questions for the Board of Supervisors**\
\
- Who within YCSO authorized a 60-day data retention period, and why does that figure differ from both Flock\'92s 30-day default and the MSA\'92s one-year maximum? Was that decision reflected in any public document, Board resolution, or contract amendment?\
\
- Flock\'92s OMNIA proposal states that all installation locations go through permitting coordination before cameras go up. Does YCSO have documentation of that permitting process for each Plumas Lake installation location? If not, were the Plumas Lake cameras installed in compliance with Flock\'92s own declared standard practice?\
\
- Given that Flock certified no proprietary information in its national cooperative contract, on what basis did YCSO withhold contract-related categories in its Phase 1 CPRA response?\
