# **17. Flock Network Scope \'97 Statewide Sharing Web and YCSO\'92s Undisclosed Partners**\
\
*Source: Flock Safety Transparency Portal sharing disclosures \'97 Antioch CA PD portal (transparency.flocksafety.com/antioch-ca-pd), reviewed April 2026. Woodland CA PD portal reviewed concurrently.*\
\
Flock\'92s Transparency Portal allows each agency to publicly disclose the organizations it shares data with, in both directions. Analysis of the Antioch PD and Woodland PD portals reveals that YCSO is embedded in a statewide (and out-of-state) sharing network that is not disclosed on YCSO\'92s own portal or in any publicly available YCSO policy document.\
\
## **Finding 1: YCSO Confirmed in Bilateral Sharing Agreements \'97 Via Third-Party Portals**\
\
Yuba County Sheriff\'92s Office appears on both the Antioch PD and Woodland PD transparency portals as a bilateral sharing partner \'97 meaning YCSO can query those agencies\'92 plate reads, and those agencies can query YCSO\'92s cameras. These are agencies operating in Contra Costa County and Yolo County respectively, roughly 80 and 40 miles from Plumas Lake.\
\
This is a strategically significant evidentiary gap: third-party public portals disclose the existence of a YCSO sharing relationship that YCSO\'92s own portal does not prominently disclose. If YCSO\'92s Phase 1 CPRA response returns no interagency data sharing agreements, or claims no responsive documents exist, the Antioch and Woodland portals serve as direct third-party rebuttal \'97 these agreements exist and are publicly acknowledged by YCSO\'92s named partners.\
\
California Vehicle Code \'a7 2413(b) requires agencies to disclose the entities with which they share ALPR data. The asymmetry between what partner agencies disclose and what YCSO discloses is itself a documentable SB 34 compliance gap.\
\
## **Finding 2: The Network Scale \'97 224 Agencies Granted Access, 267 Sharing In**\
\
The Antioch PD portal lists **224 organizations granted access to Antioch\'92s data** and **267 organizations sharing their data with Antioch**. These figures illustrate the actual operational scope of a single Flock agency\'92s sharing footprint \'97 a scope that bears no resemblance to the localized, community-safety framing typically used to justify ALPR deployments at city council and county board meetings.\
\
A Plumas Lake resident photographed by a YCSO Flock camera is not just in YCSO\'92s database. Through bilateral sharing agreements, their plate read is potentially accessible by every agency in YCSO\'92s network \'97 including, via intermediary networks, agencies hundreds of miles away with no connection to Yuba County.\
\
## **Finding 3: Out-of-State Reach**\
\
Among the agencies sharing data with Antioch are **Las Vegas Metro PD** and **Reno NV PD** \'97 Nevada law enforcement agencies with no jurisdictional relationship to California. Because YCSO participates in the same Flock network as Antioch, network-level searches by YCSO officers may reach infrastructure operated by out-of-state agencies, and vice versa. This cross-state data flow occurs entirely outside any publicly documented interagency agreement or public oversight process visible in YCSO\'92s own disclosures.\
\
## **Finding 4: Private and Commercial Entities in the Sharing Network**\
\
Five non-law-enforcement, private or commercial entities appear among the agencies sharing data *with* Antioch: **Landmark Limited Group of Companies**, **Mountain House (CA)**, **The Landing at Wildflower Station (CA)**, **Village Pointe (CA)**, and **Westwood Village**. These appear to be private residential communities or commercial property managers operating Flock cameras and feeding plate reads directly into the law enforcement network.\
\
This means the data pipeline runs in both directions beyond the law enforcement community: private entities capture plate data and share it into the Flock law enforcement network, and law enforcement data flows back out to those same private entities. Neither YCSO\'92s Policy 433 nor any publicly available YCSO document acknowledges that YCSO camera data may be accessible by private commercial operators.\
\
## **Finding 5: Federal Intelligence Infrastructure**\
\
Both **NCRIC** (Northern California Regional Intelligence Center) and the **Western States Information Network (WSIN)** appear in the Antioch granted-access list. NCRIC and WSIN are federally co-funded fusion centers that aggregate and share intelligence across law enforcement, federal agencies, and DHS. Their presence in the network means Flock plate data flows into federal intelligence infrastructure \'97 a point directly relevant to the immigration enforcement concerns that have led cities including Denver to terminate Flock contracts.\
\
## **Strategic Relevance to the Board Presentation**\
\
This finding provides the most direct counter to Supervisor Bradford\'92s anticipated \'93your phone tracks you\'94 normalization argument. The response: your phone\'92s location data does not flow bilaterally to 267 law enforcement agencies, Nevada police departments, federal fusion centers, and private residential property management companies \'97 without your knowledge, without a warrant, and without any meaningful local oversight mechanism.\
\
The Flock network is not a local tool with local accountability. It is a statewide (and interstate) surveillance infrastructure in which YCSO participates, and the scope of that participation is disclosed only on other agencies\'92 portals \'97 not YCSO\'92s own.\
\
## **Questions for the Board of Supervisors**\
\
- YCSO\'92s Transparency Portal does not list the agencies with which it shares Flock data. Antioch PD\'92s and Woodland PD\'92s portals both name YCSO as a bilateral partner. Why is this sharing relationship not disclosed on YCSO\'92s portal, as required by Vehicle Code \'a7 2413(b)?\
\
- Does YCSO have executed data sharing agreements with each of the agencies that appear on partner portals as YCSO-connected? Have those agreements been reviewed by County Counsel?\
\
- Are there written agreements governing data sharing with private or commercial Flock camera operators? If so, have those been reviewed for compliance with ALPR privacy requirements?\
\
- Does data shared through the Flock network reach federal fusion centers such as NCRIC or WSIN? If so, under what authority, and what restrictions govern federal use of locally-collected YCSO plate data?\
